Thank you for choosing to participate in this study. Please read the consent form below

 

Research Consent Form, The National Key Laboratory of Cognitive Neuroscience and Learning, Beijing Normal University

 

Purpose:

This survey investigates people鈥檚 perception of social relationships.

Procedure:

You are invited to compete a questionnaire consisting of about 100 questions and some demographic information questions.

Risks and Side Effects:

There is no risk or side effect.

Benefits: 

By completing this questionnaire, you will receive a monetary reward.

Confidentiality:

The results of this study may be published in an academic journal/book or used for teaching purposes, relevant scientific data may be shared to other researchers for further analysis. However, your name or other identifiers will not be used in any publication or teaching materials without your specific permission.

 

Do you consent to participate in this study?

column101:
"Communal Sharing" Evaluation

 

Definition: People in a 鈥楥ommunal鈥?relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently途 that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in 鈥楨xchange鈥?relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules鈥攁 benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource).

Examples: 鈥楥ommunal鈥?(e.g. husband-wife) vs 鈥楨xchange鈥?(e.g. prostitute-customer)

 

How well do you understand this dimension? - Level of understanding

column115:
"Reciprocity" Evaluation

 

Definition: The relationship is 鈥楻eciprocal鈥?if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry 鈥?receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is.

Examples: 鈥楻eciprocal/Turn-taking鈥?(e.g. between coworkers) vs 鈥楴on-Reciprocal鈥?(e.g. celebrity-fans)

 

How well do you understand this dimension? - Level of understanding

"Communal Sharing" Evaluation

 

Definition: People in a 鈥楥ommunal鈥?relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently途 that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in 鈥楨xchange鈥?relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules鈥攁 benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource).

Examples: 鈥楥ommunal鈥?(e.g. husband-wife) vs 鈥楨xchange鈥?(e.g. prostitute-customer)

"Reciprocity" Evaluation

 

Definition: The relationship is 鈥楻eciprocal鈥?if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry 鈥?receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is.

Examples: 鈥楻eciprocal/Turn-taking鈥?(e.g. between coworkers) vs 鈥楴on-Reciprocal鈥?(e.g. celebrity-fans)

 

How well do you understand this dimension? - Level of understanding
